\begin_layout Standard
I dunno.
 I have a mental block,
 for some reason.
 Maybe if I write some more,
 the mental block will go away.
 For a single,
 scalar Klein–Gordon field,
 we start by building a fiber that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 so that we build a plane bundle over each 3-D point of a space–like surface.
 We endow the plane with a symplectic form 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
-1 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

The canonical coords on the plane are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q,p\right)$
\end_inset

 but we have freedom to reparameterize with a symplectic transform 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 obeying 
\begin_inset Formula $MJM^{T}=J$
\end_inset

 and for the two-d case,
 this is any real 2-D matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with unit determinant viz 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
c & d
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $ad-bc=1$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in SL\left(2,\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 And here the games begin:
 it factors via 
\begin_inset Formula $PSL\left(2,\mathbb{R}\right)=SL\left(2,\mathbb{R}\right)/\left\{ \pm I\right\} $
\end_inset

 and has a double–covering by the metaplectic group 
\begin_inset Formula $Mp_{2}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Andre Weil gives an infinite–dimensional representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $Mp_{2n}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

 ...
 later;
 not now.
 Lets set this aside.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We take 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to be a 2D vector space,
 and construct the tensor algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(V\right)=T\left(\mathbb{R}^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The symplectic,
 uhh,
 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is used to define the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $w\otimes v-v\otimes w=w^{T}Jv$
\end_inset

 or more simply 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1}\otimes e_{2}-e_{2}\otimes e_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 or perhaps 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{q}\otimes e_{p}-e_{p}\otimes e_{q}=1$
\end_inset

 so we generate the Clifford algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(\mathbb{R}^{2}\right)/\left(\left(e_{q}\otimes e_{p}-e_{p}\otimes e_{q}=1\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This becomes the usual Weyl algebra upon identification of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{q}\mapsto x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}\mapsto d/dx$
\end_inset

 which then gets the conventional Weyl basis elements etc.
 from the PBW theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make contact with B&D,
 we have to do two things.
 First,
 write 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{q}\mapsto\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}\mapsto i\pi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 indicates that we are working at the specific fiber associated with the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 in the base (which is a space–like surface).
 At this point,
 neither 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

operators
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

;
 they are merely 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unit vectors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 whose tensor products generate the PBW basis for the Weyl algebra.
 They only become 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

operators
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 when they are actually ...
 mapped to operators!
 The mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{q}\mapsto x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}\mapsto d/dx$
\end_inset

 is just one that is possible;
 there are others (Mumford Theta,
 Arens–Micheal,
 compact–generated,
 etc.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second point of contact that needs to be taken is to write the Hamiltonian.
 To momentarily simplify the discussion,
 set the spatial derivative to zero:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\phi=0$
\end_inset

 and fix the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 so we can talk about things on just one fiber.
 This gives the Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{H}\left(\pi,\phi\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left[\pi^{2}+m^{2}\phi^{2}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Now,
 *if* 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 were real numbers,
 then the Hamiltonian flows would be counter–rotating circles,
 the only symplectic xforms leaving this invariant would be 2D rotations,
 and overall this can be identified as the simple harmonic oscillator.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 are NOT real numbers,
 they are vectors,
 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correct
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 notation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{H}\left(e_{p},e_{q}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left[e_{p}\otimes e_{p}+m^{2}e_{q}\otimes e_{q}\right]
\]

\end_inset

This allows us to identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 with an operator that acts on some appropriate function space with some appropriate topology on that space.
 That mapping would map the tensor product to whatever product is appropriate on that space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
21 March 2026
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here's the curiosity in the above.
 For the standard map 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{q}\mapsto x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}\mapsto-i\hbar d/dx$
\end_inset

 and a target space of 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 one finds that the spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is discrete;
 its the usual harmonic oscillator spectrum.
 However,
 there are other maps for 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}$
\end_inset

 and other spaces for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 to act on,
 and not all of these will have a discrete spectrum.
 Does this matter?
 I'm finding this confusing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's look at the evidence.
 Clearly,
 one wants to have a mapping where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{q}\mapsto\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as a field strength;
 i.e.
 it is what appears in couplings to other fields.
 For a scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is real;
 for a charged scalar,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is complex;
 etc for a vector field.
 But does anything depend on having 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 having the form of the Hermite polynomial(s)?
 This is not clear.
 A propagator needs to be constructed;
 the standard construction of a propagator requires a complete set of states.
 The construction does not require that these have to be the Hermites;
 any other complete set of states will do,
 as long as the resulting propagator is for a scalar,
 and that the measure on the scalar is uniform,
 viz has the standard uniform measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 What about coherent states?
 These are eigenstates of the annihilation operator,
 which is just 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{q}-ie_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Hmm.
 Well,
 I guess that the situation is forced,
 where there has to be something interpretable as a field–strength,
 and that field–strength has to be intrepretable as a probability distribution on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

,
 and this appears to force the use of 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

 as the appropriate space of of field strengths at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 But this now implies that there is a second fiber bundle:
 the one who's fiber is 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 in addition to the operator–valued fiber of which 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 are sections.
 So at least from here,
 the conventional interpretation appears to be inescapable;
 I see no loopholes.
 And yet...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is one more confusion.
 The wave–function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Phi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is a section of the second bundle;
 its value on a fiber is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{x},t\right.\left|\Phi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 but otherwise,
 as a section 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Phi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is location–less.
 The field strength at a point is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle \mathbf{x},t\right.\left|\Phi\right\rangle \right|^{2}=\left\langle \Phi\right|\left.\mathbf{x},t\right\rangle \left\langle \mathbf{x},t\right.\left|\Phi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and *this* is the quantity that must be real–valued.
 That is,
 we MUST have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle \mathbf{x},t\right.\left|\Phi\right\rangle \right|^{2}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and that THIS is the field–strength.
 So we opened up the loophole,
 again.
 We've removed the restriction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{x},t\right.\left|\Phi\right\rangle \in L^{2}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

 and it seems that we can instead have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{x},t\right.\left|\Phi\right\rangle \in F$
\end_inset

 as long as the space 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has a real–valued norm.
 The norm has to be bilinear so that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has to be a vector space,
 and we identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Phi\right|\left.\mathbf{x},t\right\rangle \in F^{*}$
\end_inset

 as belonging to the dual space.
 The space has to be complete ...
 by convention,
 it has to be a Hilbert space,
 but I am having an attack of the stupids,
 so I don't see why.
 
\end_layout

